<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-Ranova" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>ANOVA with R</title>
  <introduction>
<p> In this section we will discuss the one-way analysis of variance (ANOVA) test with R, which is used to compare the means of three or more populations to determine if at least one population mean is different from the others.  </p>
</introduction>

<objectives>
  <introduction>
    <p> At the end of this section you will be able to   </p>
  </introduction>
  <ol>
    <li> <p> Use R for one-way ANOVA. </p> </li>
    <li> <p> Interpret the results of a one-way ANOVA test in R. </p> </li>
    <li> <p> Use the format of anova(aov(numerical~categories)) </p> </li>
  </ol>
</objectives>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-R-ANOVA">
  <title>ANOVA </title>
  <p> <term>Tornado Alley</term></p>
<p> Research suggests that Tornado Alley has shifted eastward from the Great Plains with global warming.  A climate researcher wants to compare the mean annual number of tornadoes in four states: Colorado, Oklahoma, Texas, and Missouri. The researcher
      records the number of tornadoes for each state over five recent years.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Annual Number of Tornadoes</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Colorado</cell>
          <cell>Oklahoma</cell>
          <cell>Texas</cell>
          <cell>Missouri</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>48</cell><cell>67</cell><cell>132</cell><cell>41</cell></row>
        <row><cell>52</cell><cell>71</cell><cell>145</cell><cell>38</cell></row>
        <row><cell>50</cell><cell>69</cell><cell>138</cell><cell>44</cell></row>
        <row><cell>47</cell><cell>73</cell><cell>141</cell><cell>40</cell></row>
        <row><cell>53</cell><cell>68</cell><cell>136</cell><cell>42</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the mean annual number
      of tornadoes is the same for the four states.
    </p>
 
<p> Save and import the data file into R Studio. The data has already been formatted for the ANOVA test. We will be using the variables <em>Tornado</em> and <em>State</em>. </p>
<p>  <url href="external/TornadoFour.csv"> TornadoFour.csv </url> </p>
<p> <c> attach(TornadoFour)</c></p>
<p> <c> anova(aov(Tornado~State)) </c></p>
<figure xml:id="AnovaTornadoFour">
            <caption>R Studio output for Tornado ANOVA</caption>
            <image source="TornFour1.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription> The test statistic is F=934.21 and p-value is p=0.</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> <em>Interpret:</em> The test statistic is F = 934.21 and p-value of <m> p\approx 0</m> which is significant. The values under State are the between the data with df=3 and SSB=29147.3 and MSB=9715.8. The Residuals are the Within data and has df=16 and SSW=166.4 and MSW=10.40. </p> 

<p><term> Coral Reef Restoration</term></p>
     <p> A marine biologist wants to compare the mean growth of coral fragments under three different reef restoration methods. Twelve coral fragments are randomly assigned so that four fragments are treated with each method. After six months, the increase in coral length, in centimeters, is recorded.
    </p>
    <table>
      <title>Coral Growth under Three Restoration Methods</title>
      <tabular>
        <row>
          <cell>Method A</cell>
          <cell>Method B</cell>
          <cell>Method C</cell>
        </row>
        <row><cell>4.2</cell><cell>5.1</cell><cell>6.0</cell></row>
        <row><cell>4.8</cell><cell>5.4</cell><cell>6.3</cell></row>
        <row><cell>5.0</cell><cell>5.0</cell><cell>5.8</cell></row>
        <row><cell>4.5</cell><cell>5.6</cell><cell>6.1</cell></row>
      </tabular>
    </table>
    <p>
      At the <m>0.05</m> significance level, test whether the mean coral growth
      is the same for the three restoration methods.
    </p>
<p> Save and import the data file into R Studio. The data has already been formatted for the ANOVA test. We will be using the variables <em>Method</em> and <em>Growth</em>. </p>
<p>  <url href="external/Coral.csv"> Coral.csv </url> </p>
<p> <c> attach(Coral)</c></p>
<p> <c> anova(aov(Growth~Method)) </c></p>
<figure xml:id="AnovaCoralR">
            <caption>R output for Anova for Coral Growth</caption>
            <image source="Coral1.png" width="90%">
                <shortdescription> The test statistic is F=25.272 and p-value is p=0.0002</shortdescription>
            </image>
        </figure> 

<p> <em>Interpret:</em> The test statistic is F=25.272 and p-value = 0.0002029 which is significant. The values under Method are the between the data with df=2 and  SSB=4.0717 and MSB=2.03583. The Residuals has df=9 is the Within data so SSW=0.725 and MSW=0.08056. </p> 



</subsection> 





</section>
